Comment: As someone who has not lived long enough to enjoy the pleasures of reading the book or watching the original 1974 movie, and also as someone who would much prefer watching over reading, I enjoyed it very much, and am deeply dismayed at the amount of people in this comment section that did not experience as much fondness and satisfaction towards the film as I did. The cinematography was superb, and the actors were outstanding. The accents were very well done, and contrary to some people's opinions, I understood every word of it (maybe and most likely because I had help from subtitles). In conclusion, it's an amazing movie, but it is definitely only for those curious minds who don't mind too much dialogue, and who's satisfaction is not only brought by guns and explosions. 9.8/10

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: The movie "Orient Express" (all versions) was inspired by a real person, called Eugen Alimanescu, a romanian police commissioner. At the time it was called "Justice", "The invincible" or "The Iron Commissioner". In 1946, several crimes took place in the selection of the "Orient Express" train that traveled on the Paris - Bucharest - Istmabul route. These took place in the Romanian train sector, and the victims were, in turn, a Swiss diplomat and a Soviet diplomat. As cases risked taking other interpretations given the quality of the assassins, a quick resolution was required. Eugen AlimƒÉnescu, a romanian police commissar,  was responsible for solving it. He succeeded in detecting a few elements common to the two crimes, so he deduced that they were committed by the same murderer, perhaps a very stylish one considering the place where they were. Disguised as a businessman, Alimanescu managed to identify the killer and dragged him into a race. Without anything, the murderer tried to rob the "businessman" Alimanescu and at the same time to kill him. He was shot (injured), and at the hospital in Arad where he was taken to get his first aid, he died. Not before confessing the two crimes committed on the train.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I watched the movie 2 says ago and I personally don't like it whatsoever. It's forced, not interesting, no suspence, simply boring. How can you compare the creations of Penelope with Ingrid Bergman? Bergman was remarkable. The version from the 70ties is a classic. Interesting, well played, the music is just amazing. When Branagh says: "I'm Hercule Poirot, probably the most famous detective in the world", I had enough. I was sitting and waiting for the movie to end. I don't recommend at all. The only scenes I liked was when the train was leaving Istanbul, we could see some great takes of the evening city and also at the end when the train was approaching Brod, we  could see some nice takes of the mountains covered in snow. Other than that, I didn't like the movie at all. I'm still glad I watched it as now I can confirm without a doubt that the previous version is a classic that will stay a classic forever to me.

Comment: The movie was good but somehow i think the audiences were made clueless to the murderer as compared to the 1974 version with albert finney, ingrid bergmam, sean connery, lauren bacall,etc. The old version had more character development, some of the characters here (spoiler) confessed as the murderer. In the 1974 version, Poirot figured out who the murderers are without any confession from the passengers. There were also more reasons as to why some things were said (the grease on Helena's passport, Why Mrs Hubbard kept saying 2nd Husband, "Grunwald"), the face to face with Princess Dragomiroff was also incomplete and lacking information (the old version led Poirot into figuring out who Elena and Debenham were). Combining the doctor who did not murder with the colonel who did was a questionable idea, adding the fact that the colonel not only shot but confessed that he was one of the murdered....People who love this version should watch the old one too...

Comment: Just saw it. I went in just hoping for something smart with that true "keep you guessing"/"who dunnit" vibe. Delivered. I hadn't "read the book" which may be why I enjoyed it. Same as w/ Dark Tower and The Last Airbender, enjoyed both despite book fans trashing them. If you want to see this and arent familiar w/ the book don't tell anyone when you go so you can have a genuine "oh ok... I didn't see that comin" moment at the end. I'm usually "decent" at figuring out where a plot is going but impossible to get this one without prior knowledge.  My only complaint is that with a clever murder mystery I like to hear every word and line but Sometimes the character accents were a little too deep and i had to turn away from the screen to listen better lol but I didn't miss anything that prevented me from understanding the end.

Comment: Enjoyed it in a big screen today. Trust me, those beautiful train and mountains looks gorgeous on huge screen. This is the best movie of the year. 1934 is beautifully displayed in the movie. I really love those days. My grandfather and grandmother were young in those years. Anyway every actor is terrific, but the real hero is the story. The climax is really "unthinkable". Agatha Christie is really a mastermind. As for Hercule Poitor, he is a real competitor to Sherlock Holmes. And I am sure in future he will also return like SH. Overall I enjoy the movie. One last thing. The love, pain and agony of losing a loved one or see suffering of a loved one is very strong emotion. It can only a feel by a person who has gone through the experience in his\her real life. I wonder how many of our current young android generation will feel that strong emotion?

Comment:
I enjoyed this film, it's Agatha Christie reformed for a new generation It's a pity it's tanked as hard as it has. I would've loved it to be a box office smash. Yes, it is reasonably similar to every single other adaptation and it may distracting having so many big names in the film.
But I can see why Mr Branagh made this film. Christie become a niche forgotten figure in the 2010s and even though I wouldn't recommended her writing to very small children, I think that 13-14 year should read Murder on the Orient Express. It's a lesson in creativity, suspence, style and descriptive writing. In other words, it was made to make Christie fresh for today and to educate youngsters about great writing.

Comment: the movie is terribly disappointing. Firstly, I don't think the actor for Poirot really understands what he's like. It doesn't let anyone absorb inside the movie from Poirot's view. And he was also...not the Poirot type we Poirot fans know. Secondly, the actor for Macqueen is really most terrible at acting out his character--Josh Gad! Sure he's very good at Jolly characters, but not a rather serious character like Hector Macqueen. It's very different from the Macqueen I imagine. Thirdly, they changed too much from the book. I think they rather hurried through the part about interrogating the passengers, (which is actually the part for you to think)and they changed Monsieur Bouke too. I think a good suspense is to change when you must, but the key parts mustn't change. Overall, this is a good thriller, but it will never become a great suspense.

Comment: His accent is too stereotypically French. Suchet went into great lengths to not make his accent sound that way. Plus he looks too good to look like a little Belgian detective in the shape of an egg. Sorry, but this is not how Poirot is supposed to look like. In a 1924 book a first drawing of Poirot was made and Christie herself said that it was pretty close to what she envisaged him. This drawing can be seen here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poirot_Investigates . Now compare it with how all the actors depicted Poirot and you'll easily see that this one is not really close and why Suchet's portrayal is so highly rated.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
David Suchet will always be THE Hercule Poirot but dam when I first heard that the always brilliant Kenneth Branaugh was going to portray Poirot next & in a brand new big-screen adaptation of arguably Agatha Christie's most famous Poirot mystery & quite possibly her most famous story overall, I was totally floored.

I will always love both the classic original film version starring Albert Finney, Sean Connery, Anthony Perkins, Lauren Becall & Sir John Gielgud and the David Suchet version from the Poirot TV series but Branaugh as Hercule Poirot in MOTOE sounds like a serious match made in Heaven & I love the rest of the cast that they've assembled here :)

Just wish that they hadn't messed up Poirot's trademark hooked mustache here, the only flaw in this otherwise very highly promising new Poirot film :(

Comment:
I just learned that these people put an African American to play the role of Colonel Arbuthnot. There are so many Indians in England (as well as the rest of the world) and they could not find a man of Indian background to play the role of an British-Indian colonel? I thought that "they" were moving forward in the movie industry trying to bring in more Indians and people of other backgrounds onto the screen. I guess not.

I have nothing against African Americans but this is a movie about people of different backgrounds on a train. How many people are already playing an American character in that movie? I read the book years ago but I can still remember there being like 4 or 5 American characters on the train.

If they had put in a Bollywood actor in for the role of Arbuthnot, they could have attracted a whole lot more viewers to go see it in theater. Oh well.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Murder on the Orient Express was the first Agatha Christie book I ever read (and I've read all but the ones in the Miss Marple series--I'm working on it tho!) so I can't tell you how emotional I was when I first saw the cast pictures for this. I absolutely adore the larger than life take that they're doing with this. I feel like most movies and adaptations these days have to be all dark and gritty, and though a lot of Madame's works are fairly dark, there's always a sorta lightness/colorfulness that I associate with them. I can tell this movie is definitely gonna play up the classic, idk how to word it, not "goofiness", and not even "lightheartedness" but...just take a look at the website for the movie, and you'll see what I mean by how it feels like they're portraying it as if it were a game. And thats a good thing! I love it and I can't wait for this to come out! Also, yeah, I'm not the BIGGEST fan of Branagh's Poirot, but we still have to see how he does. I just hope he's not this...serious in the movie. Poirot always had a sense of humor.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Umm...what is up with the moustache? It looks like he killed a squirrel and glued it to his face.
I only bring this up, because I'm a huge fan of David Suchet's rendition of the character, not only in his acting, but also in his manner of dress reflecting his instinctual need for things to be in the proper place. His Hercule Poirot is very groomed in his waxed moustache, managed hair, and clothing. Not to mention his very thick accent, showing that French is his first, and more preferred, language.
Now what do I see with this Hercule Poirot? Messy hair, bushy unkempt moustache, crooked tie, and an accent that is very 'light'. He looks like he's going to rob the train, not solve a murder.
Also the line "I am probably the greatest detective in the world." that is quite unlike Poirot's character. If anything he says "I AM the greatest detective in the world!" as he is proud of his intellect and has the accolades to attribute to it. He's vein, but that's just apart of his character, showing that even a brilliant mind can also have flaws such as pride.

....So was this movie made?

Comment: Murder on the orient express was one of my favorite episodes on the tv show Poirot. And David Suchet not only NAILED the part of Poirot but he executed this episode with the utmost finesse. Agatha Christie wrote this book to show the humane side of Poirot highlighting a major conflict of belief. And Suchet did it justice, by the end of the episode I was bawling and applauding because very few actors have left me in awe of their performance. Suchet is Poirot. There will never be another. Saying that, I won't dismiss this movie before watching it. A lot of effort goes into movie making. To discredit it after watching a trailer seems to be rather unfair. My first book was Agatha's and my childhood was filled with a lot of Poirot watching. Now, I'm not a fan of many people in the world. But I AM a fan of Mr. David Suchet!! Good luck to this movie.

Comment: This is just so wrong on so many levels.  The cast is stellar, but the roles they play have been butchered from the source material.  Colonel Arbuthnot is now a Doctor Arbuthnot and black... in a period piece set in 1935?  Pilar Estravados now appears, despite her being in a completely different story, "Hercule Poirot's Christmas".  Foscarelli the car salesman is missing. Mr. Hardman, the private eye is now a Professor. And what on earth is that thing growing on Poirot's face?  It's almost comical in its appearance... especially when Poirot always has been proud of his mustache.  Not to mention the song choice and the supposedly opulent train shown to have little to no interior decoration or style.  Can't say I'm excited for this in the slightest.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Everyone here discussing the song, life goes on. True fans of Christie's books know this isn't just another murder mystery. This is the Queen of Crime - one of her gems: Poirot is one of the most complex, fascinating detectives ever written. Albert Finney, Peter Ustinov, and now Branagh have taken a crack at Poirot. But David Suchet is Hercule Poirot, hands down. Unfortunately, I automatically think Branagh pales in comparison, to Christie's Poirot, but that's just me. This looks too modern/2017-ish. The ambiance isn't here. Even if the plot sticks to the book perfectly, I don't sense Christie here, unlike the adaptations with Ustinov and Suchet, if that makes sense - not trying to insult Branagh/cast/writers etc. Though I do hope people viewers who watch this get excited, read her books, and watch Agatha Christie's Marple (Rutherford, Hickson, Lansbury, McEwan, and McKenzie , to decide which actress u like enjoy the most) and Poirot.
